# KPI Dashboard — Full Explanation

## Part 1: Why Did Some Numbers Change in v2?

### Quick Comparison: v1 vs v2 (4GB RAM)

| Metric | v1 | v2 | Why Changed? |
|--------|-----|-----|-------------|
| Cache Hit Rate | 98.9% | 98.8% | Tiny drop — see below |
| Load Time Reduction | -9.9% | -4.3% | Inference overhead added |
| Thrashing | 0 events | 0 events | Same — still perfect ✅ |
| Page Faults | 293 | 314 | Fewer full-RAM preloads |

### Why Cache Hit Rate Dropped Slightly (98.9% → 98.8%)

This is caused by **how tiered pre-loading classifies hits differently**:

**v1 (binary preload)**: Every preloaded app goes straight into RAM. When accessed, it counts as a **cache hit** (the app is already in `self.cache`). v1 had **29 preloads → 24 preload hits**, all counted as cache hits.

**v2 (tiered preload)**: Only **Tier 3** (>50% confidence) goes into RAM. Tier 1 and Tier 2 stay *outside* RAM:
- **Tier 1** (metadata-warm): Not in RAM → still a **cache miss** when accessed (but loads faster)
- **Tier 2** (bg-cached): Not in RAM → still a **cache miss** when accessed (but loads much faster)
- **Tier 3** (full-RAM): In RAM → **cache hit** ✅

Since the model rarely predicts a single app with >50% confidence (across 20 possible apps), most preloads land in Tier 1/2 instead of Tier 3. These still help with load time, but don't count as cache hits.

```
v1 flow:  predict > 12% → load to RAM → "cache hit" ✅
v2 flow:  predict > 10% → warm metadata → "cache miss" (but 40% faster load)
          predict > 25% → bg cache     → "cache miss" (but 80% faster load)
          predict > 50% → full RAM     → "cache hit" ✅
```

**Bottom line**: The hit rate barely moved (98.8% vs 98.9% — within 0.1%). The real benefit is that Tier 1/2 hits load much faster than cold loads, even though they're technically "misses."

### Why Load Time Improvement Dropped (-9.9% → -4.3%)

Two reasons:

**1. Inference latency overhead** (the big one)
In v2, we honestly account for the time the LSTM model takes to run predictions. Every access adds `1.5ms × 0.3 = 0.45ms` of NPU inference overhead. Over 25,636 accesses, that's `~11,500ms` of extra time the adaptive system pays that LRU doesn't.

```python
# memory_manager.py line 329
inference_overhead = self.model_inference_ms  # 1.5ms per prediction
load_time += inference_overhead * 0.3         # 30% overlaps with I/O
```

**2. Fewer full-RAM preloads** 
v1 had 29 full-RAM preloads (each saving ~50ms cold load). v2 has 0 Tier 3 preloads because at 4GB, memory is >85% full and the prediction rarely exceeds 50% for a single app.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Under **2GB memory pressure**, the load time improvement is **-23.4%** which **exceeds** the 20% target. The 4GB scenario is simply too easy — almost everything fits in RAM, so there's not much room to improve.

---

## Part 2: Every KPI Parameter Explained

### Think of it Like a Library

Imagine your phone's RAM is a **library desk** with limited space. Apps are **books**. The memory manager decides which books to keep on the desk vs which to store in a back room (storage).

---

### 1. Cache Hit Rate

**What it measures**: The percentage of times a user opens an app and it's already loaded in RAM (no disk I/O needed).

**Formula**: `cache_hits / total_accesses`

**How it works in code** ([memory_manager.py:336-354](file:///Users/parthsingla/Desktop/Coding/Project/samsung/src/memory_manager.py#L336-L354)):
```
User opens app → Is it in self.cache?
   YES → cache_hit += 1, serve from RAM (2-5ms)
   NO  → cache_miss += 1, load from storage (50-100ms)
```

**What controls it**:
- **RAM size**: More RAM = more apps fit = higher hit rate
- **Prediction quality**: Better predictions → smarter eviction → keep the right apps
- **Preloading**: Tier 3 preloads put apps in RAM before the user opens them

**Analogy**: You're at a desk. Hit rate = how often the book you need is already on your desk vs having to get up and fetch it from the shelf.

---

### 2. Avg Load Time (ms)

**What it measures**: Average time to serve an app access, across all hits and misses.

**Formula**: `total_load_time_ms / total_accesses`

**Components**:
| Scenario | Time | Code Function |
|----------|------|---------------|
| Cache hit (in RAM) | 2-5ms | `_hot_load_time()` |
| Tier 1 miss (metadata-warmed) | 30-50ms | `_tier1_load_time()` |
| Tier 2 miss (bg-cached) | 10-20ms | `_tier2_load_time()` |
| Tier 3 hit (full-RAM preload) | 3-6ms | `_tier3_load_time()` |
| Cold miss (nothing prepared) | 50-100ms | `_cold_load_time()` |

**What controls it**:
- **Hit rate**: Higher hit rate → more fast loads → lower average
- **Tiered preloading**: Even misses are faster when pre-warmed
- **Inference overhead**: ML prediction adds ~0.45ms per access
- **App size**: Larger apps (like GenAI at 800-1200MB) take longer to load

**Analogy**: Average time to get a book. If it's on your desk, instant. If you pre-ordered it from the back room, it arrives faster. If neither, you have to walk all the way to the shelf.

---

### 3. Page Faults

**What it measures**: Number of times the user accessed an app that was NOT in RAM. Each page fault requires expensive storage I/O.

**Formula**: Incremented every time `app_id not in self.cache`

**How it works** ([memory_manager.py:358-360](file:///Users/parthsingla/Desktop/Coding/Project/samsung/src/memory_manager.py#L358-L360)):
```python
if app_id not in self.cache:
    self.stats.cache_misses += 1
    self.stats.page_faults += 1  # ← every miss = page fault
```

**What controls it**:
- **Prediction-based eviction**: The eviction scoring keeps predicted-next apps in RAM, so they're there when needed
- **Tier 3 preloading**: Pre-loads apps to RAM before the user opens them
- **Anti-thrashing**: Prevents evicting apps that will be needed again soon

**Analogy**: How many times you had to get up from your desk to fetch a book. Each trip wastes time and energy.

---

### 4. Thrashing Events

**What it measures**: Rapid evict-then-reload cycles — when the system evicts an app, then the user opens it again within 30 seconds, forcing an expensive reload.

**How it's detected** ([memory_manager.py:402-403](file:///Users/parthsingla/Desktop/Coding/Project/samsung/src/memory_manager.py#L400-L405)):
```python
# During eviction:
if timestamp - page.last_access_time < 30:  # accessed < 30 seconds ago
    self.stats.thrashing_events += 1         # this was a BAD eviction!
```

**What controls it**:
- **Anti-thrashing guard**: If an app was recently evicted and reloaded, its eviction score gets a **2x boost** (harder to evict again):
  ```python
  if page.app_id in self.recent_evictions:
      if time_since_evict < 120:
          score *= 2.0  # DON'T evict this again
  ```
- **ML prediction**: The eviction scoring considers the predicted probability — if the model says "user will open this soon", it won't be evicted

**Analogy**: You put a book back on the shelf, then immediately need it again and have to go fetch it. Extremely wasteful. Our system remembers "I just put this back, don't do it again."

---

### 5. Evictions

**What it measures**: Total number of apps removed from RAM to make space for new ones.

**How eviction is decided** ([memory_manager.py:243-263](file:///Users/parthsingla/Desktop/Coding/Project/samsung/src/memory_manager.py#L243-L263)):
```
When RAM is full and a new app needs to load:

LRU (baseline): Evict the OLDEST app (least recently used)
Adaptive:       Evict the app with the LOWEST score:
                score = 0.3 × recency + 0.3 × frequency + 0.4 × ML_prediction
                ↑ lower score = less likely to be needed = evict first
```

**Scoring breakdown**:
- **Recency (30%)**: `exp(-time_since_last_use / 300)` — recently used = higher score
- **Frequency (30%)**: `access_count / max_access_count` — frequently used = higher score  
- **ML Prediction (40%)**: `prediction_probability` — predicted to be used soon = higher score
- **GenAI bonus**: 1.5× score for AI apps (expensive to reload: 800-1200MB)
- **Anti-thrash bonus**: 2× score if recently evicted and reloaded

**Analogy**: LRU = always remove the book you touched longest ago. Adaptive = remove the book you're least likely to need next, based on your reading patterns.

---

### 6. Preloads & Preload Hits

**What it measures**: 
- **Preloads**: How many apps were proactively loaded BEFORE the user opened them
- **Preload Hits**: How many of those preloads were actually useful (user did open the app)

**Tiered breakdown**:
| Tier | Trigger | What Happens | Counts As |
|------|---------|-------------|-----------|
| Tier 1 (>10%) | Metadata warm | Flash controller primed, file metadata cached | Cache miss (but 40% faster) |
| Tier 2 (>25%) | BG cache | App binary pages loaded into OS page cache | Cache miss (but 80% faster) |
| Tier 3 (>50%) | Full RAM | App mapped into RAM and initialized | Cache hit |

**How it works** ([memory_manager.py:272-318](file:///Users/parthsingla/Desktop/Coding/Project/samsung/src/memory_manager.py#L272-L318)):
```
After each app access, the predictor says:
  "Next app probabilities: WhatsApp=35%, YouTube=20%, Gmail=12%, ..."

Tier 2: WhatsApp (35% > 25%) → page into OS cache
Tier 1: YouTube (20% > 10%)  → warm storage metadata
Tier 1: Gmail (12% > 10%)    → warm storage metadata

Later, if user opens WhatsApp → Tier 2 hit! Load in 10ms instead of 50ms
```

**Analogy**: 
- Tier 1 = telling the librarian "I might need that book, please find which shelf it's on"
- Tier 2 = "bring it to the counter but don't put it on my desk yet"
- Tier 3 = "put it on my desk right now, I'm very likely to need it"

---

### 7. Energy / Battery (mJ)

**What it measures**: Total millijoule energy consumption of all memory operations.

**Cost breakdown**:
| Operation | Energy Cost | Why |
|-----------|------------|-----|
| RAM hold (LPDDR5) | 0.002 mJ/MB/sec | Keeping data in RAM takes power to refresh DRAM cells |
| Cold load (UFS 4.0) | 0.8 mJ/MB | Waking up storage controller + reading flash = expensive |
| Hot access (RAM) | 0.01 mJ/MB | Just reading already-powered RAM cells = cheap |
| NPU inference | 0.15 mJ/call | Running the LSTM model on Samsung's neural processor |
| Eviction | 0.1 mJ/MB | Flushing dirty pages back to storage |

**Why adaptive saves energy**: Fewer page faults = fewer 0.8 mJ/MB storage reads. Even though the adaptive system pays 0.15 mJ per NPU inference, it saves much more by avoiding storage I/O:

```
Saved = (443 - 314) page faults × ~180MB avg × 0.8 mJ/MB = ~18,500 mJ
Cost  = 25,636 inferences × 0.15 mJ = ~3,845 mJ
Net   = 18,500 - 3,845 = ~14,655 mJ saved (7.3%)
```

---

### 8. KV Cache Metrics

**For GenAI apps** (AI Assistant, Image Generator) that use large Key-Value caches:

| Metric | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| **Cache Reuses** | Continuation queries that reused an existing KV cache instead of allocating a new one |
| **Prefix Dedup Hits** | Requests where the system prompt was already cached and shared (no duplicate allocation) |
| **Quantizations** | KV caches compressed from FP16 to INT8 (50% size reduction) under memory pressure |
| **Offloads** | Oldest conversation turns moved from RAM to flash storage |
| **Full Evictions** | Entire KV cache entries removed when all other options exhausted |
| **Memory Saved** | Total MB saved across all optimizations |

**3-stage eviction pipeline**:
```
Memory pressure → Stage 1: Quantize (FP16→INT8, 50% smaller)
Still pressure  → Stage 2: Offload oldest 70% of conversation to storage
Still pressure  → Stage 3: Fully evict (but keep shared prefix for future reuse)
```

---

## Visual Summary: How Everything Connects

```
User opens app
      │
      ▼
┌─ Ensemble Predictor ─┐
│  "WhatsApp=35%,       │  ← prediction_accuracy (KPI)
│   YouTube=20%..."     │
└──────┬───────────────┘
       │
       ▼
┌─ Memory Check ──────────────────────────┐
│  Is app in cache?                        │
│    YES → cache_hit, hot_load (2ms)       │  ← hit_rate (KPI)
│    NO  → page_fault, check preload tier  │  ← page_faults (KPI)
│      Tier 2 hit? → bg_load (10ms)        │
│      Tier 1 hit? → warm_load (30ms)      │
│      Nothing?    → cold_load (50ms)      │  ← avg_load_time (KPI)
│                                          │
│  Need to evict for space?                │
│    score = recency + frequency + ML_pred │
│    Evict lowest → evictions (KPI)        │
│    Was recently used? → thrashing (KPI)  │
│                                          │
│  After access: run tiered preload        │
│    >50% → Tier 3 (RAM)                   │  ← preloads (KPI)
│    >25% → Tier 2 (bg cache)              │
│    >10% → Tier 1 (metadata)              │
│                                          │
│  Track energy for each operation         │  ← energy_mj (KPI)
└──────────────────────────────────────────┘
```
